  "Tax-advantaged Roth IRA vs. taxable account at the same return after 30 years:": "",
  "Same outcome since the return is identical": "",
  "Roth grows much more because there is no annual tax drag on dividends or capital gains": "",
  "Taxable account is always better due to no contribution limits": "",
  "The difference is negligible": "",
  "In a taxable account, annual dividends and realized gains reduce the compounding balance. A Roth IRA lets the full balance compound tax-free. Over 30 years, the tax drag can cost 15-25% of potential wealth.": "",
  "The fundamental equation of wealth building is:": "",
  "Borrow to invest for maximum leverage": "",
  "Invest everything regardless of expenses": "",
  "Spend more, earn more": "",
  "Earn - Spend = Savings; Invest wisely over time; Compound interest builds wealth": "",
  "Wealth building requires three steps: earn income, control spending to create savings, then invest those savings wisely. Time and compound interest do the heavy lifting, but the process starts with the discipline to save.": "",
  "What is 'survivorship bias' in fund performance data?": "",
  "When failed or closed funds are excluded from performance databases, making the average fund appear to perform better than it actually does": "",
  "The bias toward investing in established companies": "",
  "The tendency for only surviving investors to be counted in return data": "",
  "The advantage of being a long-term investor": "",
  "When poorly performing mutual funds are closed or merged, they disappear from databases. The remaining funds look better on average, creating a false impression that active management outperforms more often than it does.": "",
  "What does 'behavioral finance' study?": "",
  "The optimal trading strategies for day traders": "",
  "How psychological biases and emotional responses lead investors to make irrational decisions that harm their returns": "",
  "The behavior of stock prices during market hours": "",
  "The mathematical models behind stock pricing": "",
  "Behavioral finance identifies cognitive biases like loss aversion (feeling losses twice as strongly as gains), recency bias (overweighting recent events), and herd mentality (following the crowd) that cause investors to buy high and sell low.": "",
  "What does 'loss aversion' mean in investing?": "",
  "The tax benefit of harvesting investment losses": "",
  "Avoiding all investments to prevent any possibility of loss": "",
  "The psychological tendency to feel the pain of losses roughly twice as strongly as the pleasure of equivalent gains, often leading to poor decisions": "",
  "A strategy of stopping losses at a predetermined percentage": "",
  "Loss aversion causes investors to sell winners too early (to lock in gains) and hold losers too long (to avoid admitting a loss). It also drives panic selling during market crashes, the single most destructive investment behavior.": "",
  "What is the 'recency bias' in investing?": "",
  "Preferring recently IPO'd stocks when considering all relevant become factors": "",
  "Only investing in companies less than 5 years old, even when conditions shift significantly": "",
  "Checking your portfolio too frequently, which is a common assumption in the field": "",
  "Overweighting recent events and assuming current trends will continue, leading to buying at peaks and selling at bottoms": "",
  "After a bull market, investors become overly optimistic and invest aggressively (buying high). After a crash, they become overly pessimistic and sell (selling low). This recency-driven cycle is the opposite of rational behavior.": "",
  "What does 'total return' include?": "",
  "Only the change in stock price": "",
  "Both price appreciation (capital gains) and income (dividends and interest) combined": "",
  "Only dividend income": "",
  "Returns after subtracting all fees and taxes": "",
  "Total return = Capital Gains + Dividends/Interest. Ignoring dividends dramatically understates historical stock returns. Reinvested dividends account for roughly 40% of total S&P 500 returns since 1930.": "",
  "What is the 'disposition effect'?": "",
  "The tendency to increase investment amounts during bull markets": "",
  "The tendency to dispose of all investments at retirement": "",
  "Reducing portfolio holdings as you age": "",
  "The tendency to sell winning investments too quickly and hold losing investments too long, driven by loss aversion": "",
  "The disposition effect leads investors to take small gains quickly (selling winners) while refusing to sell losers (hoping they will recover). This is the opposite of the rational strategy of letting winners run and cutting losers.": "",
  "What does 'sequence of returns risk' mean for retirees?": "",
  "The order in which different asset classes perform each year": "",
  "The risk of inflation during retirement": "",
  "The risk of choosing investments in the wrong sequence": "",
  "The risk that poor returns in the early years of retirement, combined with withdrawals, can permanently deplete a portfolio": "",
  "A major crash in the first years of retirement forces selling at low prices to fund withdrawals, permanently reducing the portfolio. The same crash later in retirement is less damaging because fewer years of withdrawals remain.": "",
  "What does the 'wealth effect' describe?": "",
  "A guaranteed increase in wealth from investing": "",
  "When rising portfolio values make people feel richer and spend more, even if they haven't sold any investments": "",
  "The compounding effect of reinvested dividends": "",
  "The tendency for wealthy individuals to invest more": "",
  "The wealth effect is a behavioral phenomenon where paper gains increase consumer confidence and spending. It can lead to overconfidence in bull markets, causing people to take on more risk or save less than they should.": "",
  "What is 'anchoring bias' in investment decisions?": "",
  "Anchoring your portfolio to a specific benchmark index": "",
  "Investing only in well-anchored, stable companies": "",
  "Being anchored to a long-term investment strategy": "",
  "Fixating on a specific reference point (like the purchase price) and making decisions based on it rather than current fundamentals": "",
  "An investor who bought at $100 and refuses to sell at $80 'until it gets back to $100' is anchoring. The original purchase price is irrelevant to future prospects. Decisions should be based on current value and outlook, not past prices.": "",
  "What does 'herd mentality' mean in investing?": "",
  "Following the crowd into or out of investments, often buying after prices have already risen and selling after they have already fallen": "",
  "A conservative investment strategy, even when conditions shift significantly": "",
  "Investing exclusively in livestock commodities under most circumstances involving buying": "",
  "A type of agricultural investment fund, even when conditions shift significantly": "",
  "Herd mentality drove the dot-com bubble (everyone buying tech stocks in 1999) and the panic of 2008 (everyone selling at once). Following the crowd typically means buying high and selling low — the opposite of a winning strategy.": "",
