  "Two retirees each have $1,000,000 at age 65 and withdraw $40,000/year. Retiree A experiences 15% returns in years 1-3, then -10% in years 4-6. Retiree B gets -10% in years 1-3, then 15% in years 4-6. Same average return, but Retiree B:": "",
  "Has a higher balance than Retiree A, based on conventional assumptions about Retiree": "",
  "Has the same balance as Retiree A after 6 years, particularly in the context of Retiree": "",
  "Has a significantly lower balance because early losses combined with withdrawals depleted the portfolio more severely": "",
  "Has exactly $1,000,000 remaining without accounting for additional influences": "",
  "Retiree B suffered losses while also withdrawing $40K/year, permanently reducing the base that could benefit from later gains. Retiree A's early gains provided a larger buffer against later losses. This is sequence of returns risk in action.": "",
  "Real estate as a primary residence investment: a home purchased for $300,000 appreciates 3% annually to ~$403,000 after 10 years. But maintenance ($3,000/yr), property taxes ($4,000/yr), insurance ($1,500/yr), and mortgage interest ($120,000 total) add up. The true net return is:": "",
  "Higher than 3% because real estate always outperforms": "",
  "Negative, making homeownership always a bad investment": "",
  "Significantly less than 3% after accounting for all costs; the home provides housing value but is not a pure investment": "",
  "3% per year (same as appreciation)": "",
  "Appreciation gain: $103,000. Costs: maintenance ($30K) + taxes ($40K) + insurance ($15K) + mortgage interest ($120K) = $205,000. Net: -$102,000 before tax benefits. A home provides shelter value but is not purely a financial investment.": "",
