  "DALBAR's annual studies show the average investor earns 3-4% less than the market annually due to poor timing — buying after rallies and selling after declines. Over 30 years, this behavior gap costs hundreds of thousands of dollars.": "",
  "An investor with $50,000 invested 100% in one company stock watches it drop 70% to $15,000. A diversified index fund investor with the same $50,000 sees a 30% market decline to $35,000. The concentrated investor needs a _____ gain to recover; the diversified investor needs ____%.": "",
  "100% gain; 50% gain": "",
  "233% gain; 43% gain — concentration makes recovery dramatically harder": "",
  "70% gain; 30% gain": "",
  "Both need the same percentage gain": "",
  "Concentrated: $15K to $50K needs a 233% gain. Diversified: $35K to $50K needs a 43% gain. The math of losses is asymmetric — larger losses require exponentially larger gains to recover. Diversification limits the damage.": "",
  "A Roth IRA investor contributes $7,000/year for 45 years (age 22 to 67) at 8% average return. The final balance is approximately $2.68 million. The total amount contributed was:": "",
