  "During the dot-com crash (2000-2002), the NASDAQ dropped ~78%. An investor with $100,000 entirely in tech stocks saw their portfolio fall to $22,000. If they had been diversified 60/40 stocks/bonds (broad index), their portfolio would have dropped to approximately:": "",
  "$22,000 (same as tech-only), at least according to standard theory": "",
  "$100,000 (bonds offset all stock losses) under most circumstances involving portfolio": "",
  "$50,000 because conventional analysis of portfolio suggests this would be the expected result": "",
  "~$80,000 (broad stock indices fell ~30% but bonds rose, limiting the loss to ~20% on a 60/40 portfolio)": "",
  "The S&P 500 fell ~45% (less than NASDAQ's 78%), and bonds actually gained during this period. A 60/40 portfolio lost roughly 20% ($100K to $80K) compared to the tech investor's 78% loss ($100K to $22K). Diversification provided massive protection.": "",
  "A study of three investors from 1980-2020 (40 years). Investor A: worst market timer (invested $10K each year at the market peak). Investor B: best market timer (invested at the yearly low). Investor C: invested on January 1 each year regardless. At the end:": "",
  "Investor A lost money due to always buying at the peak under most circumstances involving market": "",
  "All three accumulated substantial wealth; Investor B was best but Investor A (worst timer) still grew wealth significantly because time in the market overcame poor timing": "",
  "Investor C performed worst, which represents a common but incomplete view of how these market dynamics operate": "",
  "Only Investor B made money when the interaction between market and invested factors is taken into full account": "",
  "Even the worst market timer who bought at every yearly peak accumulated enormous wealth over 40 years. The difference between best and worst timing was relatively small compared to not investing at all. Consistent investing wins over timing.": "",
  "The biggest lesson from all investing case studies is:": "",
  "Avoid the stock market entirely and stick with savings accounts": "",
  "Stock picking is more important than consistent saving": "",
  "The best investors perfectly time the market": "",
  "Start early, invest consistently, keep costs low, diversify, and stay the course through ups and downs": "",
  "Every case study reinforces the same core principles: time in the market > timing the market, low fees > high fees, diversification > concentration, discipline > emotion. These simple rules, applied consistently, build substantial long-term wealth.": ""
